orized/602-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(604, 3, '2013-07-31 16:11:48', '2013-07-31 14:11:48', 'STRATEGIES to resolve SA''s mining industry issues will need to include drastic moves towards a settled labour force and a proactive dismantling of the migrant labour system.\r\n\r\n“The effects of migrant labour are eroding the ability of mines to forge sustainable, skilled and contented communities around their operations,” says Roger Dixon, chairman of consulting engineering firm, SRK Consulting SA.\r\n\r\nDixon says much of the current labour unrest in the industry can be owed to inappropriate labour decisions taken by mines over recent years, and lack of government service provision in mine communities. It has become increasingly clear that mines'' policy of offering workers a livingout allowance for accommodating themselves has had unforeseen negative impacts, and has often exacerbated social problems in areas around mines, he argues.\r\n\r\n“The migrant labour system has endured, placing severe financial stresses on mineworkers who still try to support a life at the mine and a life back in their home village. The social and economic problems that this situation fosters have been key to recent unrest, and need to be tackled directly.”\r\n\r\nHe questions the viability of suggestions from the Presidency''s mining consultative forum that mining rosters be adjusted to allow workers more home visits each year.\r\n\r\n“It is mooted that a system of eight weeks on and two weeks off might be helpful, but this is likely to create more problems than it solves.\r\n\r\n“We should be creating the conditions to allow the workforce to settle in and around the mine environment on a permanent basis, and to focus their lives and future there.\r\n\r\n“The problem is complex, and the profitability and life span of many mines rules out some of the better options for mineworkers'' accommodation. But the solution needs to involve all stakeholders, including local government, making their contribution toward a long-term strategy for permanent urban settlements with secondary industries.”\r\n\r\nDiversifying of local economies needed to be promoted, so that communities were not overreliant on the mine itself and could outlive the mines they initially serviced. This aim, says Dixon, was already an important element of the Minerals Resources Development Act and is vital in leveraging SA''s future economy on its current mining activities.\r\n\r\nChris Jacobs, conflict resolution expert at business performance company OIM, says SA''s labour relations are at a defining moment in the country''s history.\r\n\r\n“Employers need to re-establish constructive relationships with all employees, not only union leaders, and manage both legislative challenges as well as economic demands. It is imperative that sound employee relations strategies be developed rather than short-term reactive tactics.”', 'Labour unrest compounds problems', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'labour-unrest-compounds-problems', '', '', '2013-11-11 11:27:52', '2013-11-11 09:27:52', '', 0, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/?p=604', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(605, 3, '2013-10-17 16:12:17', '2013-10-17 14:12:17', '<strong>Featured on:</strong> <a href="http://www.bdlive.co.za" target="_blank">Business Day</a>\r\n\r\nSTRATEGIES to resolve SA''s mining industry issues will need to include drastic moves towards a settled labour force and a proactive dismantling of the migrant labour system.\r\n\r\n“The effects of migrant labour are eroding the ability of mines to forge sustainable, skilled and contented communities around their operations,” says Roger Dixon, chairman of consulting engineering firm, SRK Consulting SA.\r\n\r\nDixon says much of the current labour unrest in the industry can be owed to inappropriate labour decisions taken by mines over recent years, and lack of government service provision in mine communities. It has become increasingly clear that mines'' policy of offering workers a livingout allowance for accommodating themselves has had unforeseen negative impacts, and has often exacerbated social problems in areas around mines, he argues.\r\n\r\n“The migrant labour system has endured, placing severe financial stresses on mineworkers who still try to support a life at the mine and a life back in their home village. The social and economic problems that this situation fosters have been key to recent unrest, and need to be tackled directly.”\r\n\r\nHe questions the viability of suggestions from the Presidency''s mining consultative forum that mining rosters be adjusted to allow workers more home visits each year.\r\n\r\n“It is mooted that a system of eight weeks on and two weeks off might be helpful, but this is likely to create more problems than it solves.\r\n\r\n“We should be creating the conditions to allow the workforce to settle in and around the mine environment on a permanent basis, and to focus their lives and future there.\r\n\r\n“The problem is complex, and the profitability and life span of many mines rules out some of the better options for mineworkers'' accommodation. But the solution needs to involve all stakeholders, including local government, making their contribution toward a long-term strategy for permanent urban settlements with secondary industries.”\r\n\r\nDiversifying of local economies needed to be promoted, so that communities were not overreliant on the mine itself and could outlive the mines they initially serviced. This aim, says Dixon, was already an important element of the Minerals Resources Development Act and is vital in leveraging SA''s future economy on its current mining activities.\r\n\r\nChris Jacobs, conflict resolution expert at business performance company OIM, says SA''s labour relations are at a defining moment in the country''s history.\r\n\r\n“Employers need to re-establish constructive relationships with all employees, not only union leaders, and manage both legislative challenges as well as economic demands. It is imperative that sound employee relations strategies be developed rather than short-term reactive tactics.”', 'Labour unrest compounds problems', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '604-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-10-17 16:12:17', '2013-10-17 14:12:17', '', 604, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/news/uncategorized/604-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(606, 3, '2013-07-28 16:12:34', '2013-07-28 14:12:34', 'Pretoria. – ''n Klagte van bedrog staar ''n subkontrakteur by Eskom se beleërde Medupi-bouperseel in die gesig weens foutiewe sweiswerk wat deels gelei het tot ''n vertraging van maande lank.\r\n\r\nVolgens Natasha Michael, DA-woordvoerder oor openbare ondernemings, is parlementslede verlede week hieroor ingelig tydens ''n besoek van die portefeuljekomitee vir openbare ondernemings aan die perseel.\r\n\r\nDié besoek het gepaardgegaan met arbeidsonrus Woensdag oor reistoelae waartydens vier voertuie glo aan die brand gesteek, 23 mense beseer en meer as 40 in hegtenis geneem is.\r\n\r\nDie perseel is sedertdien nog nie heropen nie. Werkers sou volgens plan Donderdagmiddag vroeg huistoe gegaan het vir ''n langnaweek. Die tyd sal leer of werk Dinsdag hervat word.\r\n\r\nEskom het onlangs aangekondig Medupi sal waarskynlik eers in die tweede helfte van volgende jaar sy eerste elektrisiteit lewer, pleks van Desember vanjaar. Dít terwyl die land bitter min reserwekrag het en ''n gebrek aan bykomende opwekkingsvermoë die ekonomie demp.\r\n\r\nVolgens Michael het amptenare van Hitachi Power Africa parlementslede ingelig die subkontrakteur het Eskom en Hitachi mislei om te glo gehalte-toetse is op die ketels uitgevoer.\r\n\r\n“Dit is nie gedoen nie. Gevolglik moes al die sweislaste op die ketel in eenheid ses weer nagegaan word en baie moes vervang word,” het sy gesê.\r\n\r\nDie DA het die indiening van strafregtelike klagte verwelkom, maar is besorg dat Hitachi die naam van die subkontrakteur verswyg. “Suid-Afrikaners moet weet watter organisasie is verantwoordelik vir die foutiewe diensverskaffing en wie Eskom en die land mislei het,” sê sy.\r\n\r\nSteven Nhlapo, sektorkoördineerder vir energie van die metaalwerkersvakbond Numsa, sê dis maklik om die skuld op die subkontrakteur te plaas. Hulle werk egter volgens spesifikasies wat aan hulle gegee word. Die sweiswerk is volgens hom oor ''n tydperk van twee jaar gedoen. Waar was Eskom se projekbestuurders dat hulle nie lont geruik het nie, vra hy.\r\n\r\nNhlapo sê Eskom se direksie moet tot verantwoording geroep word. Hulle het pres. Jacob Zuma, wat meer as ''n jaar gelede persoonlik ''n druktoets op die ketel van eenheid ses gedoen het, en die hele land vir die gek gehou, sê hy.\r\n\r\nVolgens Michael het vakbonde verlede week aan parlementslede gesê ondanks nuwe ooreenkomste en meganismes is kommunikasie tussen Eskom, kontrakteurs en vakbonde by Medupi steeds ''n probleem.\r\n\r\nDit is Woensdag onderstreep deur die onbeskermde staking, waarvan nie Eskom, die vakbonde of kontrakteurs vooraf geweet het nie, het Michael gesê.\r\n\r\nChris Jacobs, direkteur van die konsultasiefirma OIM International, sê Eskom het ''n lat vir sy eie bas gepluk deur telkens toe te gee aan werkers se eise.\r\n\r\nWerkers is vroeër vanjaar met ''n bonus teruggelok werk toe nadat bouwerk maande lank deur ''n onbeskermde staking verlam is.\r\n\r\nVolgens Jacobs word elke oorwinning vir werkers die grondslag vir ''n volgende, meer onrealistiese eis. Dit is ''n voortsetting van die tendens van bestaande loonooreenkomste in die platinumsektor wat onder druk heropen is.\r\n\r\nHy meen Eskom is onverantwoordelik, want hy werk nie met sy eie geld nie. Vir elke toegewing sal belastingbetalers later op die een of ander manier die rekening moet betaal, sê hy.\r\n\r\nJacobs sê as Eskom nie sy voet neersit nie, sal die arbeidsonrus voortduur en die kragstasie nooit klaar kom nie.\r\n\r\nDie regering, Eskom se enigste aandeelhouer, het toegang tot ''n groot deel van georganiseerde arbeid deur Cosatu, sy alliansievennoot. Húlle behoort onder mekaar ''n oplossing te vind, sê Jacobs.', 'Subkontrakteur se kop op blok', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'subkontrakteur-se-kop-op-blok', '', '', '2013-11-11 11:28:34', '2013-11-11 09:28:34', '', 0, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/?p=606', 0, 'post', '', 0),
