ng heavily solution oriented and delivering at the speed of light has been a challenge for me, but I am making good progress. Working away from home and travelling to the client on a weekly basis can be strenuous as it takes away from your after work activities (gym, sport, etc.). I used to play hockey afterhours and still hope to find a social team that I can train with in Bethal.\r\n\r\n<b>5. What are your major rewards?</b>\r\nThe experience I''m gaining through the work I do for OIM. Every day spent at work is empowering.\r\n\r\n<b>6. What do you need to succeed as an operations solutions consultant?</b>\r\nYou will need to enjoy team work and problem solving; Candidates should be able to adapt quickly to change, as project deliverables must always meet the client’s needs and will differ from project to project You need to be well rounded in your communication skills, with the ability to listen and ask questions until you grasp the issues impacting on business efficiency. Then only can you analyse and interpret the challenges to come up with meaningful solutions.\r\n\r\n<b>7. What are the minimum educational requirements for the job?</b>\r\nA tertiary level qualification is required as it enables one to think in a structured and scientific way. A post graduate degree is favoured, but not absolutely necessary. I am currently busy with my Masters in Technology Management and most of my colleagues in the operations solutions team hold postgraduate degrees. The fields of study vary and depend on the specific area of operational efficiency that one works in. The OIM team consists of consultants with Masters degrees in Chemical, Industrial and Mechanical Engineering while others hold advanced Business Management qualifications and degrees in Physics.\r\n\r\n<b>8. What is the minimum salary an operations solutions consultant can expect to earn?</b>\r\nR250K – R350K', 'Editorial submission: Rido Rambau (OIM)', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '640-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-10-17 16:43:00', '2013-10-17 14:43:00', '', 640, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/news/uncategorized/640-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(642, 3, '2013-04-17 16:45:28', '2013-04-17 14:45:28', 'Hlengiwe Skosana has been appointed as Performance Improvement Consultant at OIM, one of South Africa’s leading business performance specialists. Skosana will offer employee relations (ER) services at the company.\r\n\r\nSkosana is an International Labour Organisation (ILO) accredited commissioner trained in arbitration, mediation, conciliation labour legislation and conflict management. She has extensive experience in labour relations and conflict resolution.\r\n\r\nSkosana co-founded D-Vine Interventions, and worked as a mediator and arbitrator for the CCMA, Public Health and Welfare Bargaining Council as well as the Public Service Bargaining Council.', 'New appointment Hlengiwe Skosana', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'new-appointment-hlengiwe-skosana', '', '', '2013-10-17 16:46:01', '2013-10-17 14:46:01', '', 0, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/?p=642', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(643, 3, '2013-10-17 16:46:01', '2013-10-17 14:46:01', 'Hlengiwe Skosana has been appointed as Performance Improvement Consultant at OIM, one of South Africa’s leading business performance specialists. Skosana will offer employee relations (ER) services at the company.\r\n\r\nSkosana is an International Labour Organisation (ILO) accredited commissioner trained in arbitration, mediation, conciliation labour legislation and conflict management. She has extensive experience in labour relations and conflict resolution.\r\n\r\nSkosana co-founded D-Vine Interventions, and worked as a mediator and arbitrator for the CCMA, Public Health and Welfare Bargaining Council as well as the Public Service Bargaining Council.', 'New appointment Hlengiwe Skosana', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '642-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-10-17 16:46:01', '2013-10-17 14:46:01', '', 642, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/news/uncategorized/642-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(644, 3, '2013-04-15 16:46:13', '2013-04-15 14:46:13', 'Frans Germishuizen has been appointed as an Organisational Performance Improvement Consultant at OIM, one of South Africa’s leading business performance specialists. Germishuizen will aid companies in improving their organisational performance utilising OIM’s integrated business model.\r\n\r\nGermishuizen has 22-plus years’ experience in management and organisational performance. His key areas of expertise include business leadership, operations management and employee value creation, which is a holistic and systematic approach towards continuous organisational performance improvement. He has held several senior positions in these areas over the years, and under his leadership two of his past companies – Plascon and PPC – took top honours in the Deloitte Best Company to Work for Competition (manufacturing category) several years running.\r\n\r\nGermishuizen holds a Masters Degree in Business Leadership, a BComm and an ND in Chemical Engineering, a BComm and a Masters Degree in Business Leadership.', 'New appointment Frans Germishuizen', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'new-appointment-frans-germishuizen', '', '', '2013-10-17 16:46:31', '2013-10-17 14:46:31', '', 0, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/?p=644', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(645, 3, '2013-10-17 16:46:31', '2013-10-17 14:46:31', 'Frans Germishuizen has been appointed as an Organisational Performance Improvement Consultant at OIM, one of South Africa’s leading business performance specialists. Germishuizen will aid companies in improving their organisational performance utilising OIM’s integrated business model.\r\n\r\nGermishuizen has 22-plus years’ experience in management and organisational performance. His key areas of expertise include business leadership, operations management and employee value creation, which is a holistic and systematic approach towards continuous organisational performance improvement. He has held several senior positions in these areas over the years, and under his leadership two of his past companies – Plascon and PPC – took top honours in the Deloitte Best Company to Work for Competition (manufacturing category) several years running.\r\n\r\nGermishuizen holds a Masters Degree in Business Leadership, a BComm and an ND in Chemical Engineering, a BComm and a Masters Degree in Business Leadership.', 'New appointment Frans Germishuizen', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '644-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-10-17 16:46:31', '2013-10-17 14:46:31', '', 644, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/news/uncategorized/644-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(646, 3, '2013-04-15 16:46:40', '2013-04-15 14:46:40', 'Jaco van der Merwe has been appointed as Performance Improvement Consultant at OIM, one of South Africa’s leading business performance specialists. Van der Merwe will facilitate workshops and skills development programmes, as well as coaching clients on the implementation of OIM’s performance improvement methodology.\r\n\r\nWith a BProc degree, Van der Merwe is skilled in the areas of stakeholder engagement, legislative compliance, risk management, project management as well as process re-engineering and optimisation. He brings with him experience in leading training initiatives in the retail banking sector.\r\n\r\nVan der Merwe spent 13 years at Absa, where he began his career as a project manager, and before joining OIM, was working as a regional training consultant.', 'New appointment Jaco van der Merwe', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'new-appointment-jaco-van-der-merwe', '', '', '2013-10-17 16:47:09', '2013-10-17 14:47:09', '', 0, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/?p=646', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(647, 3, '2013-10-17 16:47:09', '2013-10-17 14:47:09', 'Jaco van der Merwe has been appointed as Performance Improvement Consultant at OIM, one of South Africa’s leading business performance specialists. Van der Merwe will facilitate workshops and skills development programmes, as well as coaching clients on the implementation of OIM’s performance improvement methodology.\r\n\r\nWith a BProc degree, Van der Merwe is skilled in the areas of stakeholder engagement, legislative compliance, risk management, project management as well as process re-engineering and optimisation. He brings with him experience in leading training initiatives in the retail banking sector.\r\n\r\nVan der Merwe spent 13 years at Absa, where he began his career as a project manager, and before joining OIM, was working as a regional training consultant.', 'New appointment Jaco van der Merwe', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '646-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-10-17 16:47:09', '2013-10-17 14:47:09', '', 646, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/news/uncategorized/646-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(648, 3, '2013-04-15 16:47:24', '2013-04-15 14:47:24', 'Kevin Setzkorn has recently been appointed as Operation Solutions Consultant at OIM, one of South Africa’s leading business performance specialists. Setzkorn will be consulting on supervisory development projects at the company as well as providing on-the-floor coaching to supervisors.\r\n\r\nPreviously, Setzkorn practised as a climate change and sustainability advisor at KPMG Services, where he worked with companies such as Implats, Eskom, BHP Billiton, Gold Fields and Standard Bank.\r\n\r\nWith a Bachelor of Science Honours in Geography and currently completing his Master of Sciences in Engineering, Setzkorn brings with him the following skills to his new position: Non-financial auditing, sustainability reporting, Global Reporting Initiative (GRI) benchmarking, lean methodology and coaching on operational efficiency.', 'New appointment Kevin Setzkorn', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'new-appointment-kevin-setzkorn', '', '', '2013-10-17 16:47:50', '2013-10-17 14:47:50', '', 0, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/?p=648', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(649, 3, '2013-10-17 16:47:50', '2013-10-17 14:47:50', 'Kevin Setzkorn has recently been appointed as Operation Solutions Consultant at OIM, one of South Africa’s leading business performance specialists. Setzkorn will be consulting on supervisory development projects at the company as well as providing on-the-floor coaching to supervisors.\r\n\r\nPreviously, Setzkorn practised as a climate change and sustainability advisor at KPMG Services, where he worked with companies such as Implats, Eskom, BHP Billiton, Gold Fields and Standard Bank.\r\n\r\nWith a Bachelor of Science Honours in Geography and currently completing his Master of Sciences in Engineering, Setzkorn brings with him the following skills to his new position: Non-financial auditing, sustainability reporting, Global Reporting Initiative (GRI) benchmarking, lean methodology and coaching on operational efficiency.', 'New appointment Kevin Setzkorn', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '648-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-10-17 16:47:50', '2013-10-17 14:47:50', '', 648, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/news/uncategorized/648-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(650, 3, '2013-03-01 16:48:03', '2013-03-01 14:48:03', 'We are at a defining moment in our country’s history. The tragic violence brought on by Marikana, the multitude of service boycotts, countless reports of corruption, ineffective policy execution and high inequality levels in South Africa, are indicators that the country has broadly-based value creation issues.\r\n\r\nA complete change in stakeholder thought and action is required at a national, industry and company level to create shared value for all.\r\n\r\nI echo Dr. Mamphela Ramphele’s recent call to build on sustainable, local, economic development programmes. However, although possible, shared value will require a complete ideology shift whereby shareholders, customers, suppliers, employees and society at large will benefit.\r\n\r\nThe central premise behind creating shared value is that the competitiveness of a country, industry or company and the wellbeing of the communities around it are mutually dependent.\r\n\r\nPositively utilising the relationship between our society and economic progress has the potential to redefine our idea of modern day capitalism. Shared value is the notion that value principles and benefits relative to cost should be applied to businesses and organisations, in order to achieve economic and social progress, and uplift society.\r\n\r\nA business that benefits its surrounding community, but utilises a model intent on benefiting all stakeholders, understands the concept of shared value. The concept is not new, as many large businesses like Barloworld, PPC Cement, Unilever and other corporates have been on that path for the past 10 years.\r\n\r\nThe concept of shared value was first coined by Michael Porter in the Harvard Business Review. The article elaborates on relevant cases where companies have developed deep and meaningful business strategies relative to their Corporate Social Investment initiatives.\r\n\r\nMining magnate Patrice Motsepe, South Africa’s wealthies black man, recently made history by announcing the donation of half his wealth to the Motsepe Foundation. In response to this action, Professor Arnold Smit, Director of the USB-ED Centre for Business in Society at the University of Stellenbosch Business School, called the decision not only historic, but a sign that wealth created through business should benefit not just owners and shareholders, but also other stakeholders in society. I agree that this decision came from a deeper inner conviction and it was done in consideration of the interests of shareholders and investors.\r\n\r\nThis announcement also came at a time when South Africa was revealed as one of the most unequal societies in the world by Oxfam, while the World Economic Forum highlighted inequality as one of the top global risks of 2013. The Oxfam report suggested that, with a Gini coefficient of 0,63 in 2011, inequality in South Africa is increasing. A Gini coefficient of zero means a country has complete equality.\r\n\r\nDigging deeper, the roots of these issues run into a society where the inequality between the haves and the haves-not is very large, and our traditional, biggest revenue spinner, our natural resources, is slowly running out. In order to move forward as a country, a huge mindset change is required for business leaders to work together in adopting ideals true the shared value approach.\r\n\r\nThe work of the National Planning Commission (NPC) can go a long way in developing a unifying vision for the country, and provide reason for stakeholders to work together. The NPC is responsible for developing a long-term strategic plan to uplift the country. However, this can only be executed under exceptional leadership.\r\n\r\nIn South Africa with its unique history, the government should take the leadership to create shared value thinking, especially to get stakeholders and role players to collaborate and engage about what needs to change.\r\n\r\nYet, South Africans have become increasingly disillusioned by the self-gain shown by people in power, both in the private and public sectors. A change in political authority has not fundamentally addressed the structural fault lines in our society. Now more than ever, the country is in need of strong and decisive leaders who can implement the concept of shared value; someone with broad-ranging credibility who is practised at understanding business processes, candidates such as Cyril Ramaphosa.\r\n\r\nAside from choosing the right candidate(s), effective goal-orientated discussion is still required, as well as action that needs to achieve by means other than through ‘talk shops’. Skill sets and capabilities of different stakeholders need to be fully utilised, in order to create a map of effective shared value approaches.\r\n\r\nThis will have to be followed by similar stakeholder forums at a civic level to focus on community value creation, involving all stakeholders in the value chain. At the same time, however, nothing stops South African businesses to lead the change that is required by adopting their own approach, vision and model to shared value creation. As the verse says, ‘where there is no vision, the people perish.’', 'DR. Mamphela Ramphele''s shared value in business: Is it possible in SA?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'dr-mamphela-rampheles-shared-value-in-business-is-it-possible-in-sa', '', '', '2013-11-11 11:36:36', '2013-11-11 09:36:36', '', 0, 'http://staging.fishgate.co.za/OIM/?p=650', 0, 'post', '', 0);
